= \n|party = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|spouse = Susan Oliver\n|children = 3\n|education = [[Tennessee Technological University|Tennessee Technological<br>University]] ([[Bachelor of Science|BS]], [[Master of Business Administration|MBA]])\n|website = {{url|estes.house.gov|House website}}\n}}\n'''Ronald Gene Estes''' (born July 19, 1956) is an American politician serving as the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for [[Kansas's 4th congressional district]] since April 25, 2017. A member of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]], he previously served as the 39th [[Kansas State Treasurer]] from 2011 to 2017 under Governor [[Sam Brownback]].\n\n==Early life, education, and career==\nEstes was born in [[Topeka, Kansas]], and is a fifth-generation Kansan.<ref name=\"StateTreasurerProfile\">{{cite news |last= |first= |date= |title=Meet Ron Estes |url=https://www.kansasstatetreasurer.com/prodweb/about_us/meet-ron-estes.php |work=Kansas State Treasurer Office of the Kansas State Treasurer and the people of Kansas |location=[[Topeka, Kansas]] |access-date=April 17, 2017 }}</ref> He earned a bachelor's degree in Civil Engineering and a master's degree in Business Administration from [[Tennessee Technological University]].<ref name=\"sedgwick\">{{cite news |last=Gruver |first=Deb |date=January 29, 2010 |title=County Treasurer Estes to run for same office at state level |url=http://www.kansas.com/news/politics-government/election/article1021871.html |work=The Wichita Eagle |location=[[Wichita, Kansas]] |access-date=April 17, 2017}}</ref>\n\nEstes worked in consulting and management roles in the aerospace, oil and gas, automotive, and several other manufacturing and service industries, working for several companies including [[Procter & Gamble]], [[Koch Industries]], and [[Bombardier Aerospace|Bombardier Learjet]].<ref name=\"CurryRollCall04122017\">{{cite news |last=Curry |first=Tom |date=April 12, 2017 |title=Estes a Stalwart but Unflashy Conservative |url=http://www.rollcall.com/news/politics/estes-profile-kansas-republican-house-race |work=[[Roll Call]] |location=[[Washington, DC]] |access-date=April 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\nHe was elected as treasurer of [[Sedgwick County, Kansas]], home to [[Wichita, Kansas|Wichita]], in 2004,<ref name=sedgwick/> and subsequently reelected in 2008.<ref name=\"CurryRollCall04122017\"/> During his political career, he also served as the Treasurer for the Kansas County Treasurer's Association, and in several posts in the Republican Party including Vice Chair of the [[Kansas Republican Party]].<ref name=\"sedgwick\"/>\n\n==Kansas State Treasurer==\nEstes ran for [[Kansas State Treasurer]] in the 2010 election, against [[incumbent]] [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]] [[Dennis McKinney]].<ref name=sedgwick/> Estes was the first statewide elected official from [[Wichita, Kansas]] in two decades.<ref name=\"StateTreasurerProfile\"/> He was reelected in 2014, defeating Carmen Alldritt.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Calovich |first1=Annie |last2=Lowry |first2=Bryan |date=November 4, 2014 |title=Republican Selzer to be next Kansas insurance commissioner |url=http://www.kansas.com/news/politics-government/election/article3568658.html |work=The Wichita Eagle |location=[[Wichita, Kansas]] |access-date=April 17, 2017}}</ref>\n\nAs state treasurer, Mr. Estes managed more than $24 billion in public money and he came in under budget by over $600,000.<ref name=\"TurkNYTimes04122017\"/> He made a priority telling Kansans about unclaimed money, such as funds from forgotten bank accounts.<ref name=\"CurryRollCall04122017\"/> In 2016, Estes said his office had returned $100 million in unclaimed property since 2010.<ref name=\"CurryRollCall04122017\"/>\n\nDuring the [[United States presidential election, 2016|2016 U.S. presidential election]], in February 2016, prior to the Kansas presidential caucuses, Estes endorsed Florida Senator [[Marco Rubio]] for the Republican nomination.<ref name=\"CurryRollCall04122017\"/> Estes served in the [[United States Electoral College|Electoral College]] and cast his electoral vote for [[Donald Trump]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kansascity.com/news/politics-government/article121772638.html|title=Missouri and Kansas Electoral College voters pick Trump, despite protests|accessdate=February 10, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"CurryRollCall04122017\"/>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n\n===Elections===\n\n====2017 Special Election====\n{{Main|Kansas's 4th congressional district special election, 2017}}\n[[Mike Pompeo]], who represented [[Kansas's 4th congressional district]] in the [[United States House of Representatives]], resigned on January 23, 2017, to become [[Director of the Central Intelligence Agency]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.c-span.org/video/?c4651445/rep-mike-pompeo-resignation-letter-read-house-senate-cia-director-confirmation|title=Rep. Mike Pompeo (R-KS04) resignation letter read in House after Senate CIA Director confirmation|accessdate=February 10, 2017}}</ref> On February 9, Estes won the Republican nomination to run in the [[Kansas's 4th congressional district special election, 2017|special election]] to determine Pompeo's successor.<ref name=\"GOPNominationEstes02092017\"/> Estes won with 66 of 126 votes in a special nominating convention held at [[Friends University]].<ref name=\"GOPNominationEstes02092017\">{{cite web|url=http://www.kansas.com/news/politics-government/article131878264.html|title=Estes wins GOP nomination for Pompeo seat|accessdate=February 10, 2017}}</ref>\n\nEstes' Democratic opponent in the special election was [[James Thompson (Kansas politician)|James Thompson]], a Wichita lawyer and veteran. Estes' special election candidacy was endorsed by many Republicans, including President [[Donald Trump]],<ref name=\"KCStarTrumpTweets\">Woodall, Hunter. [http://www.kansascity.com/news/politics-government/article143950609.html Trump tweets support for Ron Estes on special election day in Kansas\u2019 4th District], ''[[Kansas City Star]]'', April 11, 2017.</ref> Vice President [[Mike Pence]],<ref name=\"KCStarTrumpTweets\"/> Senator [[Ted Cruz]],<ref name=CruzRyanWichitaEagle>Shorman, Jonathan. Bryan Lowry & Dion Lefler. [http://www.kansas.com/news/politics-government/election/article143347764.html], ''[[The Wichita Eagle]]'', April 7, 2017.</ref> House Speaker [[Paul Ryan]],<ref name=CruzRyanWichitaEagle/> and Governor [[Sam Brownback]]. He was endorsed by the editorial board of the local newspaper, ''[[The Wichita Eagle]]''.<ref name=\"TurkNYTimes04122017\">{{cite news |last=Turkewitz |first=Julie |date=April 12, 2017 |title=Who Is Ron Estes, Kansas' Newest Congressman? |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/04/12/us/politics/ron-estes-kansas-congress-facts.html |work=[[New York Times]] |location=[[New York City]] |access-date=April 17, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe [[National Republican Congressional Committee]] contributed $92,000, in part for \"inflammatory and false\" advertisements supporting Estes, which characterized his opponent as an advocate of taxpayer-funded, late-term abortions, and also as an advocate for gender selection abortion.<ref name=\"DWeigelWashPost04102017\"/> According to April 10, 2017 fundraising reports, Estes had raised $459,000 to Thompson's $292,000.<ref name=\"DWeigelWashPost04102017\">{{cite news |last=Weigel |first=Dave |date=April 10, 2017 |title=Republicans undertake unexpected rescue mission in deep red Kansas |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/powerpost/in-kansas-a-close-congressional-race-surprises-republicans/2017/04/10/8f0085e8-1e05-11e7-ad74-3a742a6e93a7_story.html |work=[[Washington Post]] |location=[[Washington, DC]] |access-date=April 14, 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Lefler |first=Dion |date=April 8, 2017 |title=Anti-Thompson ad inflammatory and false, says professor who moderated debate |url=http://www.kansas.com/news/politics-government/article143553074.html |work=[[Wichita Eagle]] |location=[[Wichita, Kansas]] |access-date=April 16, 2017}}</ref><ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2017/04/11/us/politics/kansas-special-election.html Ron Estes, a Republican, Survives Tight House Race to Win Kansas Seat], ''[[New York Times]]'', John Eligon & Jonathan Martin, April 11, 2017. Retrieved April 12, 2017.</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Fenwick |first=Cody |date=April 12, 2017 |title=Kansas Special Election: Republican Ron Estes Wins House Seat In Tight Race |url=https://patch.com/us/white-house/kansas-special-election-results-first-test-president-trump-ballot-box |work=[[Patch.com|Patch]] |location=[[Wichita, Kansas]] |access-date=April 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\nEstes won the special election on April 11, 2017 by a margin of 52.2% to 46%.\n\n====2018 Regular Election====\n{{Main|Kansas's 4th congressional district election, 2018}}\nIn the 2018 election, the District's Republican incumbent for Congress, Representative Ron Estes is being challenged in the primaries by a candidate that shares a similar name, Ron M. Estes.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite news |last=Shorman |first=Jonathan |url=http://www.kansas.com/news/politics-government/article212306569.html |title=Ron Estes is running against Ron Estes |date=May 31, 2018 |accessdate=June 4, 2018}}</ref> This has led to a conundrum as to how the candidates should be distinguished on the ballot, with Kansas Secretary of State [[Kris Kobach]] claiming that Ron G. Estes can include the prefix \"Rep.\" on the ballot according to Kansas law, although Ron M. Estes claims that this is unfair.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n=== Tenure ===\n\nRep. Estes was sworn into office on April 25, 2017.\n\nIn December 2017, Estes voted in favor of the [[Tax Cuts and Jobs Act of 2017]].<ref name=\"Almukhtar\">{{cite web |last1=Almukhtar|first1=Sarah|title=How Each House Member Voted on the Tax Bill |url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2017/12/19/us/politics/tax-bill-house-live-vote.html?_r=1|website=The New York Times |accessdate=December 28, 2017|date=December 19, 2017}}</ref> In an [[op-ed]] for the ''[[Wichita Eagle]]'', Estes said he is \"confident it will make a real difference for families and businesses in Kansas.\" He says it will provide economic and job growth, and that workers will see larger paychecks. He says that local companies, including [[Cessna]] and [[Spirit AeroSystems]], will be able to \"compete on a level playing field with international rivals,\" as a result of the bill, and that more jobs will return to Kansas from overseas. He says the tax-filing process has been simplified, even though the process remains the same.<ref name=\"Estes122417\">{{cite web|last1=Estes|first1=Ron|title=Rep. Ron Estes: Congress delivers on tax reform|url=http://www.kansas.com/opinion/opn-columns-blogs/article191308194.html|website=kansas|accessdate=December 28, 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2017, Estes received national attention for interrupting Rep. [[Kathleen Rice]] mid-sentence while she offered a question at a Homeland Security subcommittee hearing. Rice tweeted \"Day in the life. Worth noting there are men from both parties who don't act like this\" and included a video of the exchange. Estes explained that he was simply trying to follow committee rules after Rice's time was up.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/ballot-box/344472-house-democrat-jokes-its-nice-that-not-all-male-colleagues-interrupt-her |title=House Dem jests: It's 'nice' that not all male colleagues interrupt her |date=July 29, 2017 |accessdate=June 4, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://estes.house.gov/biography/committees.htm|title=Committees {{!}} U.S. Representative Ron Estes|website=estes.house.gov|language=en|access-date=November 13, 2017}}</ref>===\n\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Education and the Workforce|Committee on Education and the Workforce]]'''\n** [[United States House Education Subcommittee on Health, Employment, Labor, and Pensions|Subcommittee on Health, Employment, Labor, and Pensions]]\n** [[United States House Education Subcommittee on Higher Education and Workforce Training|Subcommittee on Higher Education and Workforce Development]]\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Homeland Security|Committee on Homeland Security]]'''\n**[[United States House Homeland Security Subcommittee on Oversight and Management Efficiency|Subcommittee on Oversight and Management Efficiency]]\n**[[United States House Homeland Security Subcommittee on Transportation and Protective Security|Subcommittee on Transportation and Protective Security]]\n\n===Caucus memberships===\n* [[Congressional Western Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author=|url=https://westerncaucus.house.gov/about/membership.htm|publisher=Congressional Western Caucus|date=|accessdate=27 June 2018}}</ref>\n* '''[[Republican Study Committee]]'''<ref>{{cite web|title=Member List|url=https://rsc-walker.house.gov/|accessdate=November 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Political positions==\n\n===Abortion===\nEstes defines himself as \"proudly pro-life\" and he supports defunding [[Planned Parenthood]].<ref name=\"CurryRollCall04122017\" /><ref>According to Roll Call: ''On his campaign website, he said, \"I am proudly pro-life, and as your congressman, I will lead the fight to protect the unborn. One of my top priorities will be to defund Planned Parenthood. American taxpayers should not be forced to fund organizations that perform abortions.\"''</ref> In the only election debate he attended, where he joined Democrat [[James Thompson (Kansas politician)|James Thompson]], and the campaign manager for Libertarian candidate Chris Rockhold, he repeated the discredited claim that Planned Parenthood had been profiting by selling parts of aborted fetuses.<ref>[http://www.kansas.com/news/politics-government/article140363878.html Congressional front-runners Estes, Thompson clash in first debate], ''[[Wichita Eagle]]'', Dion Lefler & Daniel Salazar, March 23, 2017. Retrieved September 25, 2017.</ref>\n\n===Economic issues===\n\nHe supports a balanced-budget amendment to the Constitution and a reduction in corporate and some personal income taxes.<ref name=\"TurkNYTimes04122017\"/>\n\n===Health care===\nEstes during the 2017 special election campaign stated that he believes that the [[American Health Care Act of 2017]] did not go far enough to complete uproot and eliminate [[Obamacare]], seeking a complete repeal of the Affordable Care Act.<ref name=\"CurryRollCall04122017\" /><ref name=\"TurkNYTimes04122017\" />\n\n==Personal life==\nRon and his wife, Susan, have three children.<ref name=\"StateTreasurerProfile\"/> His family operates a farm in [[Osage County, Kansas]].<ref name=\"StateTreasurerProfile\"/>\n\n== Electoral history ==\n\n===Kansas State Treasurer===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=\"4\" |Kansas Treasurer election, 2010<ref name=\"KSSecState2010\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.kssos.org/elections/10elec/2010_General_Election_Results.pdf|title=Kansas Secretary of State 2010 Official Vote Totals|website=Kansas Office of the Secretary of State}}</ref>\n|-\n|'''Party'''\n|'''Candidate'''\n|'''Votes'''\n|'''%'''\n|-\n|Republican\n|'''Ron Estes'''\n|481,704\n|58.5\n|-\n|Democratic\n|Dennis McKinney (inc.)\n|341,324\n|41.4\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=\"4\" |Kansas Treasurer election, 2014<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.kssos.org/elections/14elec/2014%20General%20Election%20Official%20Results.pdf|title=Kansas Secretary of State 2014 Official Vote Totals|website=Kansas Office of the Secretary of State}}</ref>\n|-\n|'''Party'''\n|'''Candidate'''\n|'''Votes'''\n|'''%'''\n|-\n|Republican\n|'''Ron Estes (inc.)'''\n|570,110\n|67.5\n|-\n|Democratic\n|Carmen Alldritt\n|274,257\n|32.4\n|}\n\n===2017 Congressional election===\n\n====Republican caucus results====\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n! colspan=\"5\" {{party shading/Republican}} | Republican Convention<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thehill.com/homenews/campaign/